gomodel:SYNGO_5059  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 1b: in a series of biochemical fractions from mouse brain, transmembrane protein Elfn1 was enriched in PSD and synaptic membrane fractions.\n\nFigure 1j: Double immunofluorescence staining of the hippocampal CA1 and DG regions for Elfn1 and mGluR1a (GRM1) showed partial overlap and confirmed postsynaptic spine localization for Elfn1.\n\nFigure 2a: postsynaptic Elfn1 recruits presynaptic mGluR7 (GRM7). Overexpression of GFP-Elfn1 strongly increased mGluR7 intensity in dissociated hippocampal neurons.\n\nFigure 2c: Triple immunolabeling of endogenous Elfn1, mGluR7 (GRM7) and Vglut1 in untransfected hippocampal neurons at DIV51. mGluR7 signals overlapped with Vglut1 and were adjacent to Elfn1 signals.\n\nFigure 3: Elfn1 binds mGluR7 (GRM7) in knockout controlled reverse-immunoprecipitation.. Experimental description: Results, Figure 1 legend: \"Double immunofluorescence staining of the hippocampal CA1 and DG regions. Vibratome coronal sections from 4-month-old WT mouse brain were stained with anti-Elfn1 (magenta) and anti-mGluR1a (green).\"\n\nantibody:\n\"For production of anti-Elfn antibodies, rabbits were immunized with a synthesized C-terminal Elfn1 peptide (aa 817-828), purified Elfn1-GST (glutathione S-transferase)\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" ;
        dc:date           "2023-02-22" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_5059" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

